- [high] Visible ⋮ trigger remains non-tappable on touch (pointer-events:none kept on base rule) — src/app.css:316-330
    The fix raised the base opacity from 0 to 0.35 specifically so touch devices 'can still perceive and tap the trigger' (per the new CSS comment), but the base `.row-menu-btn` rule still sets `pointer-events: none`. pointer-events:none blocks ALL pointer input, including touch, so on a phone/tablet the now-visible ⋮ button cannot be tapped at all. The reveal conditions that switch to `pointer-events:auto` (tr:hover, tr:focus-within, .row-menu-btn:focus-visible, [aria-expanded=true]) cannot fire without first interacting with the button — which the blocked input makes impossible. Net effect: touch users see an affordance that does nothing when tapped; the only working path is an undiscoverable long-press (contextmenu) on the row. The original critical finding's keyboard half is fixed, but the touch-operability half is not — the fix is internally inconsistent with its own stated intent.
- [low] Dropdown menu items rely on browser-default focus styling — src/app.css (no :focus-visible rule for .row-menu .btn)
    The fix added explicit `:focus-visible` styling to the trigger (.row-menu-btn:focus-visible outline 2px solid #6aa6ff), but no equivalent rule exists for the menu items (`.row-menu .btn`). Focus is moved into the menu on open and navigated with Arrow Up/Down, so the currently-focused Download/Delete/Move/Copy item must show a clearly visible focus indicator. The app's convention elsewhere is an explicit #6aa6ff ring; the menu items currently fall back to the browser default outline, which is inconsistent with the rest of the app and may be absent if a global reset sets `outline: none`. This is the remaining, unaddressed half of the prior low finding (which covered 'trigger or menu items').
- [low] Tab key does not dismiss the open dropdown menu — src/app/dom-builders.ts (onMenuKey, ~280-305)
    The menu's keydown handler (onMenuKey) handles ArrowUp, ArrowDown, and Escape, but not Tab. Per the WAI-ARIA menu-button pattern, Tab closes the menu (Tab is not used to navigate within a menu). Currently, pressing Tab while focused in the menu moves focus to the next page element but leaves the dropdown open and orphaned (hidden=false, aria-expanded=true), disconnected from its trigger. A keyboard user can recover with Escape, but the lingering open menu is confusing and deviates from the expected menu interaction model.

